---
import ReportLayout from '@/components/ReportLayout.astro';
import FindingCard from '@/components/FindingCard.astro';
---

<ReportLayout title="Search Experience — Myprotein (Whey Protein)">

  <section class="report-intro">
    <h1 class="report-h1">UX Audit: Search Experience — Whey Protein</h1>
    <p class="report-meta">Myprotein Global Nav Search &mdash; Audited 5 June 2026</p>
    <p class="report-summary">
      This audit covers the end-to-end search journey for the query "Whey Protein" starting from the Best Sellers page
      (<code>/c/brandhub/best-sellers/</code>). It evaluates the search trigger, typeahead/autocomplete behaviour, query
      submission, and the destination page experience. The search contains several high-priority functional bugs and UX
      gaps that create unnecessary friction on one of the most direct paths to conversion on the site.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="findings-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Findings</h2>

    <!-- HIGH PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Clicking the search icon with no text submits an empty search"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="empty-search-submit"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Clicking the search icon (magnifying glass) in the global nav without entering any text immediately navigates
        to <code>/search/?q=</code> — an empty query — and displays 1,982 unfiltered results with no message or
        guidance. The user has no indication that nothing was searched; they are simply dropped into a wall of
        unrelated products.
        <img src="/assets/reports/myprotein-search-whey-protein-2026-06-05/above-fold-desktop.png" alt="Best Sellers page above fold showing search bar" class="finding-img" />
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        This is a direct conversion threat. Any accidental click on the search icon abandons the user's current
        context (e.g. Best Sellers) with no recovery path. 1,982 undifferentiated results also have no chance of
        converting — the user needs guidance, not a dump. This will be especially problematic on mobile where
        fat-finger taps are common.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Guard the search form submission: if the input value is empty or whitespace, prevent navigation and instead
        focus the search input and show the typeahead panel (which could surface trending or popular searches).
        The search icon click should only trigger navigation once at least one character has been entered.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Search query silently redirects to a category page — with no context given to the user"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="high"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="silent-category-redirect"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        Searching "Whey Protein" and pressing Enter does not navigate to a search results page. Instead, the user
        is silently redirected to the category page <code>/c/nutrition/protein/whey-protein/</code> titled
        "Whey Protein Powders". The search input is cleared. The breadcrumb shows the category hierarchy
        (Home &gt; Nutrition &gt; Protein Powder &amp; Protein Shakes &gt; Whey Protein Powders) — not search
        context. There is no "Search results for 'Whey Protein'" heading, no result count tied to the query, and
        no way for the user to understand what happened to their search.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Users who search expect search results — a list matching their query with relevance ranking. Silently
        redirecting to a curated category page removes user agency and breaks trust: if a user searches "Whey
        Protein Isolate" or "cheap whey protein" they may still be dropped into this generic category without
        any matching or relevance signal. It also prevents power users from using search to cross-reference
        products across categories. The query being cleared means the user cannot refine or modify their search.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Two options: (1) Preferred — navigate to a genuine search results page (<code>/search/?q=Whey+Protein</code>)
        that shows relevance-ranked results with the query pre-filled in the search input and a clear "X results
        for 'Whey Protein'" heading. (2) If the category redirect is intentional for known high-confidence queries,
        add a banner explaining the redirect: "Showing results for 'Whey Protein' — browsing Whey Protein Powders"
        and persist the query in the search input so the user can refine.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- MEDIUM PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Typeahead only triggers after 4 characters — too slow for short queries"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="typeahead-trigger-threshold"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The autocomplete dropdown does not appear after 1, 2, or 3 characters are typed. It activates after the
        4th character ("Whey"). Queries like "whey", "bcaa", "creatine", or "zinc" are common short searches
        that are fully typed before any assistance appears.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Each character typed without a response is a moment of uncertainty for the user. Industry best practice
        triggers typeahead at 2–3 characters. Delaying to 4 characters means users who type quickly will often
        have pressed Enter before they see suggestions — bypassing the helpful direct-to-product links in
        "Recommendations" entirely. This reduces the value of the autocomplete investment.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Lower the trigger threshold to 2 characters. Add a debounce of ~150ms to avoid excessive API calls.
        For single-character inputs, consider showing popular/trending searches as a fallback.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Typeahead suggestions are not highlighted — typed characters not bolded in results"
      viewport="Desktop"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="typeahead-no-highlight"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        When a user types "Whey Protein", the suggestion list shows "whey protein", "impact whey protein",
        "clear whey protein" etc. — but the matching portion of the user's query is not highlighted in bold
        or any other treatment within each suggestion. All suggestions render in the same weight and colour
        as plain text.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Lack of match highlighting is a usability regression. Users rely on the bolded portion to confirm
        their query is being matched and to quickly scan which part of the suggestion is new information.
        Without it, the list looks like a flat unsorted set of terms and requires more cognitive effort to parse.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Wrap the matched portion of each suggestion in a <code>&lt;strong&gt;</code> or <code>&lt;mark&gt;</code>
        element. For example: "impact <strong>whey protein</strong>" — where the typed characters "whey protein"
        are bolded. This is standard behaviour in all major ecommerce search implementations.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Typeahead product recommendations show no price or rating"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="design"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="typeahead-recs-no-price"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The "Recommendations" section in the typeahead dropdown displays product images and names
        (e.g. "Clear Whey Protein + Collagen", "Impact Whey Protein Milkshake") but no pricing,
        no star rating, and no review count. The user cannot assess value at a glance and must
        click through to the PDP to see price.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        The typeahead is the highest-intent moment in the discovery journey — the user is actively
        searching. Including price and ratings here (even just "£23.99 · ★4.5") gives the user
        enough buying signal to click directly to the product rather than committing to a full
        search results page. Omitting this information makes the recommendations feel like banners
        rather than actionable product links.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add price (with was/save if on promotion) and a compact star + review count to each product
        card in the typeahead. Keep cards compact — a single line below the image is sufficient.
        Spec a design to avoid layout overflow at different query lengths.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="No 'View all results' link in the typeahead dropdown"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="medium"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="typeahead-no-view-all"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The typeahead panel shows "Top Suggestions" (text links) and "Recommendations" (product cards)
        but provides no link to view all results for the query. The only way to proceed is to press
        Enter, click a suggestion, or click a product card — all of which bypass a genuine search
        results page.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Power users and users searching for comparison (e.g. "which whey protein is best value?") want
        to see a ranked list of all matching products — not just 2 recommended ones. Without a "View
        all X results" link, the typeahead becomes a dead end for these users. It also acts as a
        safety net for cases where the curated suggestions don't match the user's intent.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Add a "View all results for '[query]'" link at the bottom of the typeahead panel, linking to
        the search results page (<code>/search/?q=[query]</code>). This is a low-effort engineering
        change with high usability value.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <!-- LOW PRIORITY -->

    <FindingCard
      title="Typeahead suggestions render in all lowercase — inconsistent with brand typography"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="typeahead-lowercase-suggestions"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        All autocomplete suggestions ("whey protein", "impact whey protein", "clear whey protein" etc.)
        are rendered in lowercase even when the user has typed "Whey Protein" in title case. This is
        a minor visual inconsistency but creates a mismatch between input and suggestions.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Minor brand polish issue. Sentence case or title case presentation would look more intentional
        and match the product names shown in the "Recommendations" cards directly below.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Apply <code>text-transform: capitalize</code> or <code>text-transform: sentence</code> via CSS
        to the suggestion list items, or normalise at the data layer. Either approach is a small fix.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="aria-autocomplete attribute missing from search combobox"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="aria-autocomplete-missing"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The search input (<code>role="combobox"</code>) does not have an <code>aria-autocomplete</code>
        attribute. The DOM shows <code>aria-haspopup="dialog"</code> and <code>aria-expanded</code>,
        but <code>aria-autocomplete</code> is null. Additionally, <code>aria-expanded</code> remains
        <code>"false"</code> when the suggestion panel is open — it is not toggled to <code>"true"</code>.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Screen reader users rely on <code>aria-autocomplete="list"</code> to understand that suggestions
        will appear as they type. Without it, assistive technology may not announce the suggestion list,
        making the search inaccessible for users with visual impairments. The static <code>aria-expanded="false"</code>
        also means screen readers will not announce when the panel opens. This violates WCAG 2.1 AA
        criterion 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value).
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Set <code>aria-autocomplete="list"</code> on the combobox input. Ensure <code>aria-expanded</code>
        is toggled to <code>"true"</code> when the suggestion panel is visible and back to <code>"false"</code>
        when it closes. Also verify the suggestion panel has a valid <code>role="listbox"</code> or
        <code>role="dialog"</code> with each suggestion as <code>role="option"</code>.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

    <FindingCard
      title="Quick Buy button font size is 16px — off the 14px button spec"
      viewport="Both"
      priority="low"
      ticketType="engineering"
      ticketable={true}
      findingId="quickbuy-font-size"
    >
      <p slot="what">
        The Quick Buy CTA button on the Whey Protein category page renders at <code>font-size: 16px</code>.
        The Myprotein design token spec for buttons is <code>14px Bold</code>.
      </p>
      <p slot="why">
        Minor design consistency deviation. At 16px the button text can look heavy against the surrounding
        product card content and may subtly break the visual hierarchy of the card if other elements
        are spec'd at 14px.
      </p>
      <p slot="fix">
        Update the Quick Buy button component CSS to <code>font-size: 14px</code>. Verify no button
        instances elsewhere have been hardcoded to 16px.
      </p>
    </FindingCard>

  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Design Consistency</h2>
    <p>
      The search bar itself is visually clean — correct Figtree typeface, appropriate border radius, and a
      clear focus ring on interaction. The Quick Buy button on the destination category page uses the correct
      32px border radius and dark teal background, but is rendered at 16px font size rather than the specified
      14px. The typeahead dropdown presentation is functional but rough: suggestion text is all-lowercase with
      no type treatment hierarchy between sections ("Top Suggestions" vs "Recommendations"), and product cards
      in the dropdown lack the pricing and rating elements present on every other product surface on the site.
      The H1 on the redirected category page is 48px (on-scale) and renders correctly in Figtree. No hardcoded
      colours were detected on the primary elements inspected.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Accessibility Notes</h2>
    <p>
      The most significant accessibility issue is the incomplete ARIA implementation on the search combobox.
      The <code>aria-autocomplete</code> attribute is absent and <code>aria-expanded</code> is not updated
      dynamically when the typeahead panel opens — both are required for WCAG 2.1 AA compliance under
      criterion 4.1.2 (Name, Role, Value). This means screen reader users may receive no announcement that
      suggestions are available, effectively making the search typeahead invisible to assistive technology.
      The empty-search-submit bug (finding <code>empty-search-submit</code>) also presents an accessibility
      concern: landing on a page with 1,982 undifferentiated results with no context message creates a
      disorienting experience for any user, but particularly those relying on screen readers who must
      navigate the result list to understand where they are.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Conversion Summary</h2>
    <p>
      Search is one of the highest-intent entry points on any ecommerce site — a user typing "Whey Protein"
      has high purchase intent. The current experience has two conversion-critical failures: the accidental
      empty-search submit drops users into an unusable 1,982-result dump, and the silent category redirect
      strips the user of their search context entirely. Of the two, the silent redirect is the more
      structurally damaging — it means every search that matches a known category bypasses the search
      results page, removing relevance ranking, cross-category comparison, and query refinement. Users
      who land on the Whey Protein Powders category page with no query context have lost the thread of
      their search intent. The typeahead medium-priority issues (late trigger, no highlights, no price/ratings,
      no view-all link) represent compounding friction that reduces the value of the typeahead investment —
      all are fixable without backend changes. Together these issues make the search experience the weakest
      conversion surface currently on the site.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="prose-section">
    <h2 class="section-heading">Recommended Implementation Order</h2>
    <ol class="recommendations">
      <li>
        <strong>Fix empty-search submit bug</strong> — prevent icon click from navigating when input is empty;
        redirect focus to input and open typeahead with trending searches instead. (Engineering, ~1 day)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Persist query after search submission</strong> — whether redirecting to category or search results,
        keep the typed query in the search input and add a visible "Results for 'X'" heading. (Engineering, ~1 day)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Add 'View all results' link to typeahead</strong> — link to <code>/search/?q=[query]</code>
        at the bottom of the dropdown. (Engineering, ~half day)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Lower typeahead trigger to 2 characters</strong> — with 150ms debounce. (Engineering, ~half day)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Add match highlighting to suggestions</strong> — bold the typed query within each suggestion string.
        (Engineering, ~half day)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Add price and rating to typeahead product cards</strong> — spec required from design before build.
        (Design + Engineering, ~2 days)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Fix ARIA on search combobox</strong> — add <code>aria-autocomplete="list"</code> and dynamic
        <code>aria-expanded</code> toggle. (Engineering, ~half day)
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Fix Quick Buy font size</strong> — set to 14px per design tokens. (Engineering, ~1 hour)
      </li>
    </ol>
  </section>

</ReportLayout>

<style is:global>
  .finding-card code {
    font-family: Menlo, Monaco, 'Courier New', monospace;
    font-size: 12px;
    background: var(--color-bg-muted);
    padding: 1px 5px;
    border-radius: 4px;
    color: var(--color-text-heading);
  }
</style>

<style>
  .report-intro { margin-bottom: 40px; }
  .report-h1 { font-size: 26px; font-weight: 800; color: var(--color-text-heading); line-height: 1.25; margin-bottom: 6px; }
  .report-meta { font-size: 13px; color: var(--color-text-body); opacity: 0.65; margin-bottom: 14px; }
  .report-summary { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); max-width: 680px; }
  .findings-section { margin-bottom: 48px; }
  .section-heading { font-size: 18px; font-weight: 700; color: var(--color-text-heading); margin-bottom: 20px; padding-bottom: 10px; border-bottom: 2px solid rgba(0, 57, 66, 0.1); }
  .prose-section { margin-bottom: 36px; }
  .prose-section p { font-size: 15px; line-height: 1.7; color: var(--color-text-body); }
  .recommendations { padding-left: 20px; display: flex; flex-direction: column; gap: 10px; }
  .recommendations li { font-size: 14px; line-height: 1.6; color: var(--color-text-body); }
</style>
